The paper deals with the application of deep convolutional neural networks for medical image analysis, specifically for the segmentation of white matter hyperintensities in brain MR images. This falls under the computer vision (cs.CV) sub-category. The paper proposes several deep CNN architectures that consider multi-scale patches or take explicit location features while training, indicating a focus on machine learning (cs.LG) and artificial intelligence (cs.AI) techniques. The paper also discusses the performance levels of the machine and the independent human observer, suggesting a possible interest in neural networks (cs.NE) and human-computer interaction (cs.HC).
